First change the `id` attributes to `className` instead. id&#39;s are only meant to be used on one element and this will render every question or answer with the same id.

Then in your css file you can style them with: 

```
.questions{
  // Question styles here
}

.answers {
 // Answer styles here
}
```

Then import your css file.

Just a suggestion, but you may want to utilize react&#39;s templating a little more heavily.  It makes things much easier to read and manage.  Also, you should only use a unique ID on one single element.  Multiple elements with the same ID interferes with accessibility and scripts that may depend on fetching a single element.  Additionally, semantically speaking, your list is better off if each item is consolidated into question-answer pairs.
```html
  &lt;li class=&quot;item&quot; rt-repeat=&quot;question in this.props.questions&quot;&gt;
    &lt;span class=&quot;question&quot;&gt;
      {question[&quot;text&quot;]}
    &lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;span class=&quot;answer&quot; rt-if=&quot;this.dummy&quot;&gt;
      {this.props.answers[questionIndex-1]}
    &lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;/li&gt;
```

Your css can then be used to style these classes in order to make them appear on the right or the left side.  For example, the way I was able to accomplish this is by using relative positioning and assigned widths.
Remember, `75%` + `25%` = `100%` only works if `box-sizing` is set to `border-box`.

